<div class="body"><p> Worse, this goes to competence. Even those who do not warm to Mr Osborne acknowledge his skill at the great game of politics. It is in large part this grandmaster status that makes him the favourite to succeed David Cameron. Simply, people don't love Mr Osborne, but they think he's good at what he does. </p><p> So what now? There'll be plenty of people telling him to back down, soften the tax credit cuts (<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/georgeosborne/11944905/Cutting-tax-credits-to-reduce-inheritance-tax-punishes-work-and-rewards-unearned-privilege.html">here's my suggestion from last week</a>) and make the package acceptable to the Lords (and Tory colleagues). </p><p> But that would have costs, possibly severe ones. It would prove that Mr Osborne is vulnerable, susceptible to pressure – mortal. He'd stay in the race to succeed Mr Cameron, but he'd take a wound that would slow him up; he might go from prohibitive favourite to just one of the pack. Losing favourite status can be damaging. </p><p>
