</div><p></p><p> The other option carries bigger risks, and bigger rewards: stand firm, lay siege to the Lords and wage bloody political war to pass the tax credits package as written. Make this a point of fundamental political principle, the defining battle of the Parliament and his career: who governs Britain – unelected lefty peers, or George Osborne? That would be no mean feat, since it might require some controversial measures (100 Tory chums made peers, anyone?) and mean turning public opinion (broadly sceptical about cutting tax credits) against the Lords. </p><p> One thing is clear: he needs to kill the Lords' tax credit timetable. <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/georgeosborne/11951056/Tax-credits-what-are-they-who-claims-them-and-why-is-everyone-so-angry-about-the-cuts.html" target="_blank">Three million people being told you're making them worse off</a> one year into the Parliament is one thing. The same cuts falling a year before the 2020 general election is quite another. </p><p> I mentioned 2012. Another part of Mr Osborne's recent success with colleagues is his ability to know when to learn from setbacks (he softened his harsh public person) and when to stand firm (he didn't waver on the 50p tax rate). If he can pull off a similar trick this time, acknowledging and accepting public doubts about tax credits without budging on his fundamental goals, he may well be truly unbeatable in the succession game. </p><p> Mr Osborne loves the political game, perhaps even too much. A great deal rides on the next hand he plays. </p><p> <iframe class="tg-card" data-id="002a4ab2-88b9-4c76-965b-c50de54b8a43" frameborder="0" height="259" id="player1" scrolling="no" src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/breakoutCards/002a4ab2-88b9-4c76-965b-c50de54b8a43.html" style="float: left; margin: 0px 0px 10px; height: 1124px;" width="540"></iframe><script src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/assets/_scripts/embed-card.js"></script>  </p></div>

